<setup>
  
  <function name="f">2+3/(1+(x+1)^2)</function>
  <derivative name="fP">$f</derivative>
  <derivative name="fPP">$fP</derivative>

  <math name="fP1symbolic">(-2*(x+1))/(1+(x+1)^2)^2</math>
  <math name="fP2symbolic">-2*(x+1))*(1+(x+1)^2)^(-2)</math>   

  <math name="crNum1">-1</math>
  <mathList name="correctCrNums"> $crNum1 </mathList>

  <text name="correctfINCR1">(-INF, -1)</text>
  <text name="correctfINCR2">(-INF,-1)</text>
  <text name="correctfDECR1">(-1, INF)</text>
  <text name="correctfDECR2">(-1,INF)</text>

  
  <!--
  <math name="POI1">a</math>
  <math name="POI2">(a+b)/2</math>  
  <mathList name="correctPOIs"> $POI1 $POI2 </mathList>
  -->
  
</setup>  


<p>
  Let <m>f(x) = 2 + \frac{3}{1+(x+1)^2}</m>.
</p>

<p>
  <ol marker="a.">
    <li>
      <p>
        Find <m>f'(x)</m> and use it to determine all of the critical numbers of <m>f</m>.  If there is more than one critical number, enter them as a list separated by commas.  If there are none, enter <em>none</em>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>f'(x) = </m><mathInput name="fPentered"/>
        <answer simplifyOnCompare>
          <award><when>
            $fPentered = $fP1symbolic or $fPentered = $fP2symbolic or
          </when></award>
        </answer>
      </p>
      <p>
        The critical numbers of <m>f</m> occur at <m>x = </m> <mathInput name="crNums" /> <answer unorderedCompare><award><when> $crNums=$correctCrNums</when></award></answer>.
      </p>  
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Construct a first derivative sign chart for <m>f</m> and thus determine all intervals on which <m>f</m> is increasing or decreasing.  State your results in the following blanks.  For example, if <m>f</m> is increasing on the intervals <m>(-\infty, 2)</m> and <m>(5,\infty)</m>, enter <q>(-INF, 2), (5, INF)</q> (that is, separate the intervals with commas).  If <m>f</m> is never increasing, enter <q>never</q>. 
      </p>  
      <p>
        The function <m>f</m> is increasing for <textInput name="fINCR"/><answer type="text"><award><when>$fINCR = $correctfINCR1 or $fINCR = $correctfINCR2</when></award></answer>.
      </p>  
      <p>
        The function <m>f</m> is decreasing for <textInput name="fDECR"/><answer type="text"><award><when>$fDECR = $correctfDECR1 or $fINCR = $correctfDECR2$</when></award></answer>.
      </p>  
    </li>  
    <li>
      <p>
        Explain why <m>f(x) \gt 2</m> for every value of <m>x</m> by completing the following sentence.
      </p>
      <p>
        Since <m>(x+1)^2</m> is always <answer><choiceInput inline>
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>positive</choice>
          <choice credit="1">non-negative</choice>
          <choice>not positive</choice>
          <choice>negative</choice>
        </choiceInput></answer>, it follows that <m>1 + (x+1)^2</m> is always <answer><choiceInput inline>
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>negative</choice>    
          <choice credit="1">positive</choice>
        </choiceInput></answer>, and therefore <m>\frac{3}{1 + (x+1)^2}</m> is also always <answer><choiceInput inline>
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>negative</choice>    
          <choice credit="1">positive</choice>
        </choiceInput></answer>.  These observations imply that  <m>f(x) = 2 + \frac{3}{1 + (x+1)^2}</m> is always <answer><choiceInput inline>
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>less than 2</choice>    
          <choice>less than or equal to 2</choice> 
          <choice>greater than or equal to 2</choice>   
          <choice credit="1">greater than 2</choice>
        </choiceInput></answer>.
      </p>  
    </li>  
    <li>
      <p>
        Determine <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \to \infty} f(x)</m> and <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \to -\infty} f(x)</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \to \infty} f(x) = \lim_{x \to \infty} 2 + \frac{3}{1 + (x+1)^2} = </m><answer>2</answer>
      </p>  
      <p>
        <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \to -\infty} f(x) = \lim_{x \to -\infty} 2 + \frac{3}{1 + (x+1)^2} = </m><answer>2</answer>
      </p> 
    </li>  
    <li>
      <p>
        Complete the following sentence to explain why <m>f</m> has a global maximum and to state its value (as an ordered pair of the form <m>(a,b)</m>, where <m>b = f(a)</m>).
      </p>  
      <p>
        Based on our work in (a) and (b), the function <m>f</m> has a global maximum because for <m>x \lt -1</m>, <m>f</m> is <answer><choiceInput inline>
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>always decreasing</choice> 
          <choice>always concave down</choice>
          <choice credit="1">always increasing</choice> 
          <choice>always concave up</choice>
        </choiceInput></answer>, and for <m>x \gt -1</m>, <m>f</m> is <answer><choiceInput inline>
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice credit="1">always decreasing</choice> 
          <choice>always concave down</choice>
          <choice>always increasing</choice> 
          <choice>always concave up</choice>
        </choiceInput></answer>; the global maximum occurs at the point (enter your answer as an ordered pair) <answer>($crNum1,$$f($crNum1))</answer>.
      </p>  
    </li>  
    <li>
      <p>
        Finally, complete the following sentence to explain why <m>f</m> does not have a global minimum.
      </p> 
      <p>
        Based on our work in (c) and (c), the function <m>f</m> does not have a global minimum because while <m>f(x)</m> is <answer><choiceInput inline>
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>always less than 2</choice> 
          <choice>always equal to 2</choice>
          <choice credit="1">always greater than 2</choice> 
        </choiceInput></answer>, since <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \to \pm \infty} f(x) = </m><answer>2</answer>, for any value of <m>f(x)</m> that we find, no matter how close that number is to <m>2</m>, we can always find another value of <m>f(x)</m> that is <answer><choiceInput inline>
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>larger, but still less than 2</choice> 
          <choice credit="1">smaller, but still larger than 2</choice>
          <choice>smaller, but still less than 2</choice>
          <choice>larger, but still greater than 2</choice>
        </choiceInput></answer>, so there is no output of <m>f(x)</m> that is less than or equal to every possible output of the function.
      </p>  
    </li>  
  </ol>
</p>  
